5":"1405","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, Anglie","of Towersey, Buckinghamshire, England":"Towersey, Buckinghamshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Arundel Castle, Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel, Sussex, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1353–1425":"omkring 1353–1425","1350–1405":"1350–1405","1383–1470":"1383–1470","1390–Male":"1390–Afdød","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1425":"1425","about 1380":"omkring 1380","25 July 1405":"25. juli 1405","1353":"1353","1383":"1383","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","about 1353":"omkring 1353","1390":"1390","1405":"1405","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","of Towersey, Buckinghamshire, England":"Towersey, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Arundel Castle, Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel, Sussex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1353–1425":"circa 1353–1425","1350–1405":"1350–1405","1383–1470":"1383–1470","1390–Male":"1390–Overleden","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1425":"1425","about 1380":"circa 1380","25 July 1405":"25 juli 1405","1353":"1353","1383":"1383","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","about 1353":"circa 1353","1390":"1390","1405":"1405","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","of Towersey, Buckinghamshire, England":"Towersey, Buckinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Arundel Castle, Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1353–1425":"about 1353–1425","1350–1405":"1350–1405","1383–1470":"1383–1470","1390–Male":"1390–Deceased","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1425":"1425","about 1380":"about 1380","25 July 1405":"25 July 1405","1353":"1353","1383":"1383","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","about 1353":"about 1353","1390":"1390","1405":"1405","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","of Towersey, Buckinghamshire, England":"Towersey, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Arundel Castle, Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"FitzAlan","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: relationship name from Anglo-Norman French  <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ (  see  Fitz  ) + the personal name  <i>Alan</i> (  see  Allen  ), ‘son of  <i>Alan</i>’."],"variants":[{"name":"Fitz","meanings":["English: from Anglo-Norman French <i>fi(t)z</i> ‘son’ (from Latin <i>filius</i>), used originally to distinguish a son from a father bearing the same personal name and then conventionalized as a hereditary surname, or short for a surname of which <i>fiz</i> ‘son’ was the first element, for example   Fitzhenry   and   Fitzroy  .","Altered form of English   Fitch  .","German: from a vernacular pet form of the personal name <i>Vinzenz</i> (see   Vincent  ) or <i>Vitus</i> (see   Vito  , compare   Veit  ). Compare also   Fietz  ."]},{"name":"Allen","meanings":["English and Scottish: from the Middle English, Old French personal name <i>Alain</i>, <i>Alein</i> (Old Breton <i>Alan</i>), from a Celtic personal name of great antiquity and obscurity. In England the personal name is now usually spelled <i>Alan</i>, the surname <i>Allen</i>; in Scotland the surname is more often <i>Allan</i>. From 1139 it was common in Scotland, where the surname also derives from Gaelic <i>Ailéne</i>, <i>Ailín</i>, from <i>ail</i> ‘rock’. The present-day frequency of the surname Allen in England and Ireland is partly accounted for by the popularity of the personal name among Breton followers of William the Conqueror, by whom it was imported first to Britain and then to Ireland. Saint Alan(us) was a 5th-century bishop of Quimper, who was a cult figure in medieval Brittany. Another Saint Al(l)an was a Cornish or Breton saint of the 6th century, to whom a church in Cornwall is dedicated.","English: occasionally perhaps from the rare Middle English femaje personal name <i>Aline</i> (Old French <i>Adaline</i>, <i>Aaline</i>), a pet form of ancient Germanic names in <i>Adal-</i>, especially <i>Adalheidis</i> (see   Allis  ).","French: variant of   Allain  , a cognate of 1 above, and, in North America, (also) an altered form of this."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Margaret FitzAlan was born about 1353, in Arundel, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. She married John Collingridge about 1380, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1425, in her hometown, at the age of 73."},"et":{"about 1353–1425":"umbes 1353–1425","1350–1405":"1350–1405","1383–1470":"1383–1470","1390–Male":"1390–Surnud","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1425":"1425","about 1380":"umbes 1380","25 July 1405":"25. juuli 1405","1353":"1353","1383":"1383","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1470":"1470","about 1353":"umbes 1353","1390":"1390","1405":"1405","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England":"West Wycombe, Buckinghamshire, England","of Towersey, Buckinghamshire, England":"Towersey, Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Arundel Castle, Arundel, Sussex, England":"Arundel, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1353–1425":"noin 1353–1425","1350–1405":"1350–1405","1383–1470":"1383–1470","1390–Male":"1390–Kuollut","1353–1425":"1353–1425","1425":